			<div class="content" id="post-content-1124010">
									

<p>I like it.</p>
<p>There are a few bits that could be clarified, like what happens if you play the film back multiple times: is multiple copies created?</p>
<p>Also, the length of the film is unrealistic, even for the Foundation. An average 2 hour long movie has 3801.6 meters of film stock (that's about 2.36 miles of film!). (I found this by multiplying the length of one side of 35mm film, which is ~22mm, by 24 fps, divided by 1000 to convert into meters, and then multiplied by 60 for #frames per minute, times 120 for frames per two hours.) For a 289 hour long film, you'd need 549331.2 meters of film (or 341.34 miles of film!) That's just ridiculously large.</p>
<p>Cut it down to 24 hours or so, maybe even 48. That should help with the realism of this. (Yes, I know, I'm a massive nerd. Shush.)</p>
<p>Other than that, just some minor grammar errors that you'll need to fix. Good concept, decent execution, nice premise! Upvoted.</p>

							</div>

								
					
